vateer America; captured when Arnold burned New London, Sept 6, 1781"}],"bio":{"title":"Captain","display_name":"Captain William Coit","nickname":"The Great Red Dragon","notes":"Known for wearing a scarlet cloak","first_name":"William","last_name":"Coit","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1761"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Captain of one of America's first warships","body":"In late 1775 he commanded the schooner Harrison — one of the first vessels commissioned by Congress under General Washington. He intercepted two British supply ships and brought them into Plymouth harbor."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Made British prisoners stand on Plymouth Rock","body":"He landed the captured British prisoners on Plymouth Rock, where they 'gave three cheers, and wished success to American arms,' per the Pennsylvania Journal of 1775. The act inverted Plymouth's founding myth: now British prisoners stood on the rock."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"The Great Red Dragon — scarlet cloak","body":"He was tall, portly, soldierly in bearing, frank, jovial, somewhat eccentric, and very liberal. He wore a scarlet cloak that earned him the nickname 'The Great Red Dragon.'"},{"number":4,"category":"military","header":"First American to invert the British flag","body":"He claimed to be 'the first man in the States who turned his majesty's bunting upside down' when he captured British vessels in late 1775. The symbolic act came early in the naval war."},{"number":5,"category":"military","header":"“Cohorns that Noah had in the Ark”","body":"His November 1775 letter savaged his own schooner: cannon “brought by the Lords Say and Seal” in 1635, swivels “never fired since” 1620, a deck that broke through over the magazine